'''Corona Australis''' is a [[constellation]] in the [[Southern Celestial Hemisphere]]. Its Latin name means "southern crown", and it is the southern counterpart of [[Corona Borealis]], the northern crown. It is one of the 48 constellations listed by the 2nd-century astronomer [[Ptolemy]], and it remains one of the 88 modern constellations. The Ancient Greeks saw Corona Australis as a wreath rather than a crown and associated it with [[Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]] or [[Centaurus]]. Other cultures have likened the pattern to a turtle, ostrich nest, a tent, or even a hut belonging to a [[rock hyrax]].

Although fainter than its northern counterpart, the oval- or horseshoe-shaped pattern of its brighter stars renders it distinctive. [[Alpha Coronae Australis|Alpha]] and [[Beta Coronae Australis]] are the two brightest stars with an apparent magnitude of around 4.1. [[Epsilon Coronae Australis]] is the brightest example of a [[W Ursae Majoris variable]] in the southern sky. Lying alongside the [[Milky Way]], Corona Australis contains one of the closest [[Star formation|star-forming regions]] to the [[Solar System]]—a dusty [[dark nebula]] known as the [[Corona Australis Molecular Cloud]], lying about 430 light years away. Within it are stars at the earliest stages of their lifespan. The variable stars [[R Coronae Australis|R]] and [[TY Coronae Australis]] light up parts of the nebula, which varies in brightness accordingly.

== Name ==

The name of the constellation was entered as "Corona Australis" when the [[International Astronomical Union]] (IAU) established the 88 modern constellations in 1922.<ref name="IAUTransactions3">{{cite conference |url=http://www.ianridpath.com/iaulist1.htm |title=Proceedings of the 1st General Assembly |date=1922 |conference=Transactions of the International Astronomical Union |location=Rome |volume=1 |pages=158 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ianridpath.com/iaulist1.htm |title=IAU constellation list 1 |last=Ridpath |first=Ian |accessdate=2017-01-06 }}</ref>
In 1932, the name was instead recorded as "Corona Austrina" when the IAU's commission on notation approved a list of four-letter abbreviations for the constellations.<ref name="IAUTransactions4">{{cite conference |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/transactions-of-the-international-astronomical-union/volume/631391278F71D28204CE2F1B0925CD77?pageNum=2 |last1=Schlesinger |first1=F. |last2=Schilt |first2=J. |date=1932 |conference=Transactions of the International Astronomical Union |location=Cambridge |volume=4 |pages=221–222 |title=Meetings of Commissions. Commission 3. (Notations.) |doi=10.1017/S0251107X00016631 }}</ref>
The four-letter abbreviations were repealed in 1955.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ianridpath.com/iaulist2.htm |title=IAU constellation list 2 |last=Ridpath |first=Ian |accessdate=2017-01-06 }}</ref> The IAU presently uses "Corona Australis" exclusively.{{sfn|IAU, ''The Constellations'', Corona Australis}}

== Characteristics ==

Corona Australis is a small constellation bordered by [[Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]] to the north, [[Scorpius]] to the west, [[Telescopium]] to the south, and [[Ara (constellation)|Ara]] to the southwest. The three-letter abbreviation for the constellation, as adopted by the [[International Astronomical Union]] in 1922, is "CrA".{{sfn|Russell|1922|p=469}} The official constellation boundaries, as set by [[Eugène Joseph Delporte|Eugène Delporte]] in 1930, are defined by a polygon of four segments (''illustrated in infobox''). In the [[equatorial coordinate system]], the [[right ascension]] coordinates of these borders lie between {{RA|17|58.3}} and {{RA|19|19.0}}, while the [[declination]] coordinates are between −36.77° and −45.52°.{{sfn|IAU, ''The Constellations'', Corona Australis}} Covering 128 square degrees, Corona Australis [[culmination|culminates]] at midnight around the 30th of June{{refn|name=Malin Frew 1995 p218}} and ranks 80th in area.{{sfn|Ridpath, ''Constellations''}} Only visible at latitudes south of [[53rd parallel north|53° north]],{{sfn|Ridpath, ''Constellations''}} Corona Australis cannot be seen from the British Isles as it lies too far south,{{refn|name=Moore & Tirion 1997 pp164}} but it can be seen from southern Europe{{refn|name=Moore 2005 p202}} and readily from the southern United States.{{refn|name=Moore 'Stargazing' 2000 p86}}

== Features ==
[[File:Constellation Corona Australis.jpg|thumb|left|The constellation Corona Australis as it can be seen by the naked eye]]
While not a bright constellation, Corona Australis is nonetheless distinctive due to its easily identifiable pattern of stars,{{sfn|Ridpath|Tirion|2017|pp=126–127}} which has been described as horseshoe-{{refn|name=Falkner 2011 p100}} or oval-shaped.{{refn|name=Malin Frew 1995 p218}} Though it has no stars brighter than 4th magnitude, it still has 21 stars visible to the unaided eye (brighter than magnitude 5.5).{{sfn|Bakich|1995|p=130}} [[Nicolas Louis de Lacaille]] used the Greek letters Alpha through to Lambda to label the most prominent eleven stars in the constellation, designating two stars as Eta and omitting Iota altogether. [[Mu Coronae Australis]], a yellow star of spectral type G5.5III and apparent magnitude 5.21,{{sfn|SIMBAD Mu Coronae Australis}} was labelled by [[Johann Elert Bode]] and retained by [[Benjamin Apthorp Gould|Benjamin Gould]], who deemed it bright enough to warrant naming.{{sfn|Wagman|2003|pp=114–115}}

=== Stars ===
{{see also|List of stars in Corona Australis}}
The only star in the constellation to have received a name is [[Alpha Coronae Australis|Alfecca Meridiana or Alpha CrA]]. The name combines the [[Arabic]] name of the constellation with the [[Latin]] for "southern".{{sfn|Allen|1963|pp=172–173}} In Arabic, ''Alfecca'' means "break", and refers to the shape of both Corona Australis and Corona Borealis.{{sfn|Kaler, ''Alfecca Meridiana''}} Also called simply "Meridiana",{{sfn|Bagnall|2012|p=170}} it is a white [[main sequence]] star located 125 light years away from Earth,{{sfn|Ridpath|Tirion|2017|pp=126–127}} with an [[apparent magnitude]] of 4.10 and [[Stellar classification|spectral type]] A2Va.{{sfn|SIMBAD Alpha Coronae Australis}} A rapidly rotating star, it spins at almost 200&nbsp;km per second at its equator, making a complete revolution in around 14 hours.{{sfn|Royer|Zorec|Gómez|2007|p=463}} Like the star [[Vega]], it has [[Infrared excess|excess infrared radiation]], which indicates it may be ringed by a disk of dust.{{sfn|Kaler, ''Alfecca Meridiana''}} <!-- cites two previous sentences --> It is currently a [[main-sequence star]], but will eventually [[stellar evolution|evolve]] into a [[white dwarf]]; currently, it has a luminosity 31 times greater, and a radius and mass of 2.3 times that of the Sun.{{sfn|Kaler, ''Alfecca Meridiana''}} [[Beta Coronae Australis]] is an orange [[giant star|giant]] 474 light years from Earth.{{sfn|Ridpath|Tirion|2017|pp=126–127}} Its spectral type is K0II, and it is of apparent magnitude 4.11.{{sfn|SIMBAD Beta Coronae Australis}} Since its formation, it has evolved from a [[B-type star]] to a [[K-type star]]. Its [[luminosity class]] places it as a [[bright giant]]; its luminosity is 730 times that of the Sun,{{sfn|Kaler, ''Beta Coronae Australis''}} designating it one of the highest-luminosity K0-type stars visible to the naked eye.{{sfn|Bagnall|2012|p=170}} 100 million years old, it has a radius of 43 [[solar radius|solar radii]] ({{Solar radius}}) and a mass of between 4.5 and 5 [[solar mass]]es ({{Solar mass}}). Alpha and Beta are so similar as to be indistinguishable in brightness to the naked eye.{{sfn|Kaler, ''Beta Coronae Australis''}}

Some of the more prominent double stars include [[Gamma Coronae Australis]]—a pair of yellowish white stars 58 light years away from Earth, which orbit each other every 122 years. Widening since 1990, the two stars can be seen as separate with a 100&nbsp;mm aperture telescope;{{sfn|Ridpath|Tirion|2017|pp=126–127}} they are separated by 1.3 arcseconds at an angle of 61 degrees.{{sfn|Moore|Rees|2011|p=413}} They have a combined visual magnitude of 4.2;{{sfn|SIMBAD LTT 7565}} each component is an F8V [[dwarf star]] with a magnitude of 5.01.{{sfn|SIMBAD HR 7226}}{{sfn|SIMBAD HR 7227}} [[Epsilon Coronae Australis]] is an [[Binary star#Eclipsing binaries|eclipsing binary]] belonging to a class of stars known as [[W Ursae Majoris variable]]s. These star systems are known as [[Contact binary|contact binaries]] as the component stars are so close together they touch. Varying by a quarter of a magnitude around an average apparent magnitude of 4.83 every seven hours, the star system lies 98 light years away.{{sfn|Kaler, ''Epsilon Coronae Australis''}} Its spectral type is F4VFe-0.8+.{{sfn|SIMBAD Epsilon Coronae Australis}} At the southern end of the crown asterism are the stars [[Eta¹ Coronae Australis|Eta¹]] and [[Eta² Coronae Australis]], which form an [[optical double]].{{sfn|Motz|Nathanson|1991|pp=254–255}} Of magnitude 5.1 and 5.5, they are separable with the naked eye and are both white.{{sfn|Streicher|2008|pp=135–139}} [[Kappa Coronae Australis]] is an easily resolved optical double—the components are of apparent magnitudes 6.3 and 5.6 and are about 1000 and 150 light years away respectively.{{sfn|Ridpath|Tirion|2017|pp=126–127}} They appear at an angle of 359 degrees, separated by 21.6 arcseconds.{{sfn|Moore|Rees|2011|p=413}} [[Kappa2 Coronae Australis|Kappa²]] is actually the brighter of the pair and is more bluish white,{{sfn|Streicher|2008|pp=135–139}} with a spectral type of B9V,{{sfn|SIMBAD HR 6953}} while [[Kappa1 Coronae Australis|Kappa¹]] is of spectral type A0III.{{sfn|SIMBAD HR 6952}} Lying 202 light years away, [[Lambda Coronae Australis]] is a double splittable in small telescopes. The primary is a white star of spectral type A2Vn and magnitude of 5.1,{{sfn|SIMBAD Lambda Coronae Australis}} while the companion star has a magnitude of 9.7. The two components are separated by 29.2 arcseconds at an angle of 214 degrees.{{sfn|Moore|Rees|2011|p=413}}

[[Zeta Coronae Australis]] is a rapidly rotating main sequence star with an apparent magnitude of 4.8, 221.7 light years from Earth. The star has blurred lines in its hydrogen spectrum due to its rotation.{{sfn|Motz|Nathanson|1991|pp=254–255}} Its spectral type is B9V.{{sfn|SIMBAD Zeta Coronae Australis}} [[Theta Coronae Australis]] lies further to the west, a yellow giant of spectral type G8III and apparent magnitude 4.62.{{sfn|SIMBAD Theta Coronae Australis}} Corona Australis harbours [[RX J1856.5-3754]], an isolated [[neutron star]] that is thought to lie 140 (±40) parsecs, or 460 (±130) light years, away, with a diameter of 14&nbsp;km.{{sfn|Ho Wynn C. G. et al.|2007}} It was once suspected to be a [[Quark star#Strange star|strange star]],{{sfn|Drake, Jeremy J. et al.|2002}} but this has been discounted.{{sfn|Ho Wynn C. G. et al.|2007}}

=== Deep sky objects ===

[[File:R Coronae Australis region.jpg|thumb|The R Coronae Australis region imaged with the Wide Field Imager at [[ESO]]'s [[La Silla Observatory]]. According to ESO, "The light blue nebulosity seen in this picture is mostly due to the reflection of starlight off small dust particles." "A prominent dark lane crosses the image from the centre to the bottom left. Here the visible light emitted by the stars that are forming inside the cloud is completely absorbed by the dust. These objects could only be detected by observing at longer wavelengths, by using a camera that can detect infrared radiation."]]

In the north of the constellation is the [[Corona Australis Molecular Cloud]], a dark [[molecular cloud]] with many embedded [[reflection nebula]]e,{{sfn|Kaler, ''Beta Coronae Australis''}} including [[NGC 6729]], [[NGC 6726]]–7, and [[IC 4812]].{{sfn|Malin|2010}} A [[star formation|star-forming region]] of around {{Solar mass|7000}},{{sfn|Kaler, ''Beta Coronae Australis''}} it contains [[Herbig–Haro object]]s ([[protostar]]s) and some very young stars.{{sfn|Malin|2010}} About 430 light years (130 parsecs) away, it is one of the closest star-forming regions to the Solar System.{{sfn|Reipurth|2008|p=735}} The related NGC 6726 and 6727, along with unrelated NGC 6729, were first recorded by [[Johann Friedrich Julius Schmidt]] in 1865.{{sfn|Steinicke|2010|p=176}} The [[Coronet cluster]], about 554 light years (170 parsecs) away at the edge of the [[Gould Belt]], is also used in studying star and [[protoplanetary disk]] formation.<ref>{{cite journal
|last=Sicilia-Aguilar|first=Aurora
|last2=Henning|first2=Thomas
|last3=Juha´sz|first3=Attila
|last4=Bouwman|first4=Jeroen
|last5=Garmire|first5=Gordon
|last6=Garmire|first6=Audrey
|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=687
|issue=2
